T1  - The Role of Information in Repeated Games With Frequent Actions
AU  - Sannikov, Yuliy
AU  - Skrzypacz, Andrzej
Y1  - 2010/05/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA6420
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 847
EP  - 882
VL  - 78
IS  - 3
KW  - Repeated games
KW  - imperfect monitoring
KW  - frequent actions
KW  - Brownian motion
KW  - Poisson process
KW  - Levy decomposition
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA6420
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We show that in repeated interactions the avenues for effective provision of incentives depend crucially on the type of information players observe. We establish this conclusion for general repeated two-player games in which information arrives via a continuous-time stationary process that has a continuous multidimensional Brownian component and a Poisson component, and in which the players act frequently. The Poisson jumps can be used to effectively provide incentives both with transfers and value burning, while continuous Brownian information can be used to provide incentives only with transfers.
ER  - 

