TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fear of Miscoordination and the Robustness of Cooperation in Dynamic Global Games With Exit
AU  - Chassang, Sylvain
Y1  - 2010/05/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA7324
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 973
EP  - 1006
VL  - 78
IS  - 3
KW  - Cooperation
KW  - fear of miscoordination
KW  - global games
KW  - dynamic games
KW  - exit games
KW  - local dominance solvability
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA7324
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper develops a framework to assess how fear of miscoordination affects the sustainability of cooperation. Building on theoretical insights from Carlsson and van Damme (1993), it explores the effect of small amounts of private information on a class of dynamic cooperation games with exit. Lack of common knowledge leads players to second guess each other's behavior and makes coordination difficult. This restricts the range of equilibria and highlights the role of miscoordination payoffs in determining whether cooperation is sustainable or not. The paper characterizes the range of perfect Bayesian equilibria as the players' information becomes arbitrarily precise. Unlike in one-shot two-by-two games, the global games information structure does not yield equilibrium uniqueness.
ER  - 

